Requirement Description

This violin diagram is very advanced and suitable for comparing differences.

https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00497-018-00357-2 fromhttps://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00497-018-00357-2

Figure S4. Integrative Analysis of Aging-Associated Differentially Expressed Genes with Genes from GenAge or POF/POI Database, Related to Figure 4 (A) Violin plots showing expression levels of marker genes for each cell type in young (Y) and old (O) monkey ovaries.

Application Scenarios

The three characteristics are displayed in comparison at the same time. Just like the example in this diagram, the distribution of gene expression under three characteristics is compared: cell type, marker gene, and age.

There are two forms of input data for you to choose from, which is seamless with single-cell data and very friendly to non-single-cell data.

Here are a few examples:

  • Figure 1H, heat map and bubble map correspond to the results of expression profiling and gene function enrichment analysis, please refer to FigureYa206scHeatmap;
  • Figure 3AB, the relationship between gene expression patterns and cell types can be seen from the PCA results, please refer to FigureYa222PCAgene;
  • Figure 4B, showing the up- and down-regulated genes in two colors, see FigureYa232scRankHeatmap;

In addition, Figure S6H uses color and shape to display the grouping information at two levels, which can be drawn by referring to FigureYa101PCA.

Input files

Choose between single-cell and non-single-cell data:

  • Single-cell data. sc.seurat.Rdata, file obtained from single-cell RNA-seq pretreatment. How do I get this document? Drag to the end of the article to see Attached: Single-cell RNA-seq data preprocessing
  • Non-single-cell data. easy_input.csv, as long as your data also has three characteristics, organized into a easy_input.csv appearance, you can draw such a graph.

Single-cell data

load("sc.seurat.Rdata")
markers <- c("DDX4", "AMH", "COL1A2", "ACTG2", "CDH5", "KLRB1", "CD163")

df <- FetchData(sc, vars = c(markers, "aging", "cluster_short")) %>%
  reshape2::melt(id.vars = c("aging", "cluster_short"), 
                 variable.name = "gene",
                 value.name = "expression") %>%
  mutate(aging = factor(aging, levels = c("Y", "O")),
         cluster_short = factor(cluster_short, levels = c("OO","GC", "SC", "SMC",  "EC", "NKT", "M")))

# 
# Save to a file for easy formatting
write.csv(df, "easy_input.csv", quote = F, row.names = F)

easy_input.csv

Non-single-cell data

easy_input.csv, the first three columns are the three features you want to group, and the last column is a specific value, which is shown in the graph.

df <- read.csv("easy_input.csv", header = T)

# 
# Sort according to your own requirements, the order corresponds to the order in the figure
df$aging <- factor(df$aging, levels = c("Y", "O"))
df$cluster_short <- factor(df$cluster_short, levels = c("OO","GC", "SC", "SMC",  "EC", "NKT", "M"))
df$gene <- factor(df$gene, levels = c("DDX4", "AMH", "COL1A2", "ACTG2", "CDH5", "KLRB1", "CD163"))

Start drawing

The figure shows cluster_short horizontally and genes vertically, and each cell is grouped by aging to plot the distribution of gene expression.

Reproduce the original text

ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(aging, expression, fill = aging)) +
  geom_violin(show.legend = F) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("grey", "cornflowerblue")) + #  # The two groups are filled with gray and blue, respectively
  facet_grid(gene~cluster_short) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("Expression level (log TPM)") +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        strip.background.x = element_rect(fill = "lavenderblush"), #  # Top padded pink
        strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0),
        strip.background.y = element_blank())

ggsave("scViolin.pdf", width = 9, height = 7)

Beautified version

My friend thinks the color of the original picture is ugly, so lets modify the color.

ggplot(df, mapping = aes(aging, expression, fill = aging, color = aging)) +
  #geom_violin(show.legend = F) + # violin # Draw violin
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#2874C5", "#EABF00")) + #  # The two groups are filled with blue and yellow, respectively
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#2874C5", "#EABF00")) + #  # The border is the same color as the fill
  
  # box plot
  # If you like, you can overlay box plots
  geom_boxplot(outlier.size = -1, 
               show.legend = FALSE, #  # Legend is not displayed
               color="black", lwd=0.2, #  # The thickness of the line
               alpha = 0.7) + #  # Transparency
  #  # Scatters can also be overlayed
  geom_point(shape = 21, size=.6, #  # The shape and size of the dots
             show.legend = FALSE, #  # Legend is not displayed
             position = position_jitterdodge(), 
             alpha = 0.3)+ 
  # geom_violinviolinbox
  # You can even comment the line of geom_violin, don't draw violin, only box and scatter
  
  facet_grid(gene ~ cluster_short) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("Expression level (log TPM)") +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        strip.background.x = element_rect(fill = "grey95"), #  # The top is filled with light gray
        strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0),
        strip.background.y = element_blank()) 

ggsave("scViolin_color.pdf", width = 9, height = 7)

Enhanced

With the help of ggpubr plus pvalue or salient star*, the method of adding pvalue to facets refers to this https://www.datanovia.com/en/blog/how-to-add-p-values-to-ggplot-facets/

stat.test <- df %>% 
  group_by(cluster_short, gene) %>% 
  t_test(expression ~ aging) %>%
  adjust_pvalue(method = "bonferroni") %>% 
  add_significance()

                     hide.ns = TRUE, #M ~ DDX4NaN0 # The non-significant ones will not be displayed, and there is a special case here that NaN appears in M ~ DDX4 in the upper right corner of the figure, because the expression level of all samples in this group is 0
                     label = "{p.adj}{p.adj.signif}", # pvalue # pvalue and star
                     label.size = 3, # pvalue # The size of the pvalue word
                     vjust = -0.5) + # pvalue # The upper (negative) lower position of the pvalue
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.1))) #pvalue # Leave enough space for pvalue text

Read data

umi <- read.table(file = gzfile("GSE130664_merge_UMI_count.txt.gz"), header = T, row.names = 1, sep = "\t")
qc <- readxl::read_excel("1-s2.0-S0092867420300568-mmc1.xlsx", sheet = 2)
meta <- readxl::read_excel("1-s2.0-S0092867420300568-mmc1.xlsx", 3) %>% 
  column_to_rownames("cell")

Data preprocessing

See Methods:
QUANTIFICATION AND STATISTICAL ANALYSIS -> Single-Cell RNA-Seq Data Processing

# QC of Cells
cells <- qc %>% 
  filter(`Mapping rate` >= 0.2 &
           `Gene number` >= 700 &
           UMI >= 3000) %>%
  pull(Rename)

# seurat object
sc <- CreateSeuratObject(counts = umi[,cells], meta.data = meta)

# expression transformation
sc@assays$RNA$data <- sc@assays$RNA$counts %>% 
  apply(2, function(x){
    log2(10^5*x/sum(x)+1)
    })

# remove other cells
sc <- sc[,sc$cluster != "other"]

# cluster
# Rename the cluster
sc$cluster_short <- factor(
  plyr::mapvalues(sc$cluster, 
                  c("Oocyte", "Natural killer T cell", "Macrophage",
                    "Granulosa cell", "Endothelial cell", 
                    "Smooth muscle cell", "Stromal cell"),
                  c("OO", "NKT", "M", "GC", "EC", "SMC", "SC")),
  levels = c("OO", "NKT", "M", "GC", "EC", "SMC", "SC"))

# cluster
# Customize the color for the cluster
cluster_colors <- setNames(brewer.pal(7, "Set1"), levels(sc$cluster_short))

# 
# Save it so you can stop and run
#save(sc, cluster_colors, file = "sc.seurat.Rdata")

# 
# It is also possible to output the expression matrix to a file
#write.csv(sc@assays$RNA@data, "easy_input_expr.csv", quote = F)
